DP  - 2012 Feb
TI  - Collaboration in mindfulness-based cognitive therapy.
PG  - 179-86
LID - 10.1002/jclp.21832 [doi]
AB  - In this article, we describe the nature of therapeutic collaboration between 
      psychotherapist and group participants in mindfulness-based cognitive therapy 
      (MBCT), which occurs in a group format and incorporates cognitive therapy and 
      mindfulness practices with the aim of preventing depression relapse. 
      Collaboration is a central part of two components of MBCT: inquiry and leading 
      mindfulness practices. During the process of inquiry, the therapist-initiated 
      questions about the participant's moment-to-moment experience of the practice 
      occurs in a context of curious, open, and warm attitudes. In addition, 
      collaboration is maintained through co-participation in mindfulness practices. We 
      provide a case illustration of collaboration in these contexts and conclude with 
      recommendations for clinical practice.
