TI  - Patient predictors of response to cognitive behaviour therapy and interpersonal 
      psychotherapy in a randomised clinical trial for depression.
PG  - 252-61
LID - 10.1016/j.jad.2010.07.002 [doi]
AB  - OBJECTIVES: This study examined patient predictors of response to interpersonal 
      psychotherapy (IPT) and cognitive behaviour therapy (CBT). METHOD: Participants 
      were 177 adults with a primary diagnosis of major depressive disorder randomised 
      to 16 weekly sessions of either IPT or CBT. Pre and post treatment depressive 
      symptomatology was assessed by an independent clinician with the Montgomery 
      Asberg Depression Rating Scale. RESULTS: General predictors of response were 
      perceived logic of therapy, recurrent depression and childhood reasons for 
      depression (r² =.21). Only one differential predictor of treatment response was 
      identified. Increasing comorbid personality disorder symptoms was associated with 
      decreases in response to IPT but not CBT. CONCLUSION: The results indicate that 
      attention to specific pretreatment patient factors may enhance response to 
      psychotherapy.
